{"id": "qdo1665702738098", "title": "Configuring Uniface Applications to Use TLS", "breadcrumbs": ["Configuring Uniface and Uniface Applications", "Configuring Uniface Applications to Use TLS"], "url": "https://docs.rocketsoftware.com/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/qdo1665702738098.html", "html": "<html><body><header class=\"zDocsTopicPageHead\"><h1 class=\"css-g931ng\">Configuring Uniface Applications to Use TLS</h1><div class=\"zDocsTopicActions\" role=\"list\"><div class=\"zDocsBundlePagination\" data-testid=\"next-prev-container\" role=\"listitem\"><div class=\"zDocsPrevTopicButton zDocsPrevTopicButton\"><span class=\"\"><a aria-label=\"Previous:  Configure a Different Database as the Repository  \" class=\"\" data-tooltip-content=\"Previous:  Configure a Different Database as the Repository  \" data-tooltip-id=\"zDocsTopicActionsTooltip\" data-tooltip-open=\"false\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/nbh1665702774909.html\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-prev\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-prev\"></use></svg></a></span></div><div class=\"zDocsNextTopicButton zDocsNextTopicButton\"><span class=\"\"><a aria-label=\"Next: Support for Distributed Applications \" class=\"\" data-tooltip-content=\"Next: Support for Distributed Applications \" data-tooltip-id=\"zDocsTopicActionsTooltip\" data-tooltip-open=\"false\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/ure1665702745274.html\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-next\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-next\"></use></svg></a></span></div></div><div class=\"zDocsMyDocsMenu\" role=\"listitem\"><span aria-expanded=\"false\" aria-label=\"Add to My Topics\" class=\"d-none d-lg-flex\" data-toggle=\"dropdown\" data-tooltip-content=\"Add to My Topics\" data-tooltip-id=\"zDocsTopicActionsTooltip\" id=\"addToMyDocsDropdownTrigger\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-bookmark-add\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-bookmark-add\"></use></svg></span><span class=\"d-lg-none d-flex\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-bookmark-add\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-bookmark-add\"></use></svg>Add to My Topics</span><div aria-labelledby=\"pdfDropdown\" class=\"dropdown-menu dropdown-menu-right\"><a class=\"zDocsAddTopicButton zDocsMyDocsMenuItem dropdown-item\" href=\"/de-DE/auth/login?redirect=/bundle/uniface_104/page/qdo1665702738098.html?finish_action=mydocs_topic_and_sub\">Add selected topic and subtopics</a><a class=\"zDocsAddTopicButton zDocsMyDocsMenuItem dropdown-item\" href=\"/de-DE/auth/login?redirect=/bundle/uniface_104/page/qdo1665702738098.html?finish_action=mydocs_topic_and_sub_head\">Add Topic &amp; Subtopics with topic head</a><a class=\"zDocsAddTopicButton zDocsMyDocsMenuItem dropdown-item\" href=\"/de-DE/auth/login?redirect=/bundle/uniface_104/page/qdo1665702738098.html?finish_action=mydocs_pub\">Add entire publication</a></div></div><div class=\"zDocsWatchButton\" role=\"listitem\"><span aria-label=\"Watch\" class=\"d-lg-flex d-none zDocsSubscribeButton\" data-tooltip-content=\"Watch\" data-tooltip-id=\"zDocsTopicActionsTooltip\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-eye\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-eye\"></use></svg></span><span class=\"d-lg-none d-flex zDocsSubscribeButton\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-eye zDocsSubscribeButton\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-eye\"></use></svg><span class=\"zDocsSubscribeButton\">Watch</span></span></div><div class=\"zDocsExportPdfMenu zDocsExportMenu\" data-testid=\"export-pdf-menu\" role=\"listitem\"><span aria-expanded=\"false\" aria-label=\"Download PDF\" class=\"d-none d-lg-flex\" data-toggle=\"dropdown\" data-tooltip-content=\"Download PDF\" data-tooltip-id=\"zDocsTopicActionsTooltip\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-pdf\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-pdf\"></use></svg></span><span class=\"d-lg-none d-flex\" data-return-focus=\"#zDocsTopicActionsMobile\" data-target=\"#ZdExportPDFModal\" data-toggle=\"modal\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-pdf\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-pdf\"></use></svg>Download PDF</span><div class=\"dropdown-menu zDocsDropdownMenu\"><a class=\"zDocsExportItem zDocsExportTopicButton\" href=\"#\" id=\"singlePdf\" role=\"button\">Save selected topic</a><a class=\"zDocsExportItem zDocsExportSubtopicsButton\" href=\"#\" id=\"pdfWithChildren\" role=\"button\">Save selected topic and subtopics</a><a class=\"zDocsExportItem zDocsExportBundleButton\" href=\"#\" id=\"wholeBundlePdf\" role=\"button\">Save entire publication</a></div></div><div class=\"zDocsTopicShare zDocsShareButton\" role=\"listitem\"><span aria-expanded=\"false\" aria-label=\"Share\" class=\"d-none d-lg-flex zDocsShareDialogButton\" data-toggle=\"dropdown\" data-tooltip-content=\"Share\" data-tooltip-id=\"zDocsTopicActionsTooltip\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-share\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-share\"></use></svg></span><span class=\"d-lg-none zDocsShareDialogButton\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-share\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-share\"></use></svg>Share</span><div class=\"dropdown-menu zDocsDropdownMenu\"><a class=\"dropdown-item zDocsShareButton zDocsShareEmail\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\"><span>Email Link</span></a><a class=\"dropdown-item zDocsShareButton zDocsShareLink\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\"><span>Copy Link</span></a></div></div><div class=\"zDocsFeedback zDocsFeedback zDocsTopicFeedback\" role=\"listitem\"><span aria-label=\"Feedback\" class=\"zDocsFeedbackButton d-none d-lg-flex\" data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_main_3615370\" data-toggle=\"modal\" data-tooltip-content=\"Feedback\" data-tooltip-id=\"zDocsTopicActionsTooltip\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-feedback\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-feedback\"></use></svg></span><span class=\"d-lg-none d-flex zDocsFeedbackButton\" data-backdrop=\"static\" data-return-focus=\"#zDocsTopicActionsMobile\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_main_3615370\" data-toggle=\"modal\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-feedback\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-feedback\"></use></svg><span class=\"zDocsFeedbackButtonText\"> Feedback</span></span></div></div><div class=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><button aria-label=\"Show topic actions\" data-toggle=\"dropdown\" id=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-ellipsis-h\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-ellipsis-h\"></use></svg></button><div class=\"dropdown-menu zDocsDropdownMenu zDocsTopicActionsMobileDropdown dropdown-menu-right\"></div></div><div style=\"flex-basis: 100%; height: 0px;\"></div><ul class=\"zDocsTopicPageDetails\"><li class=\"zDocsTopicPageDate css-cinqea\">Last Updated<span class=\"css-cinqea\">Okt 05, 2024</span></li><li class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryDetailsItem\"><button class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryButton\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-topic-summary\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-topic-summary\"></use></svg>Summarize</button></li><li class=\"spacer\" role=\"presentation\"></li><div class=\"zDocsLabelWrapper\"><ul><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: Uniface\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=prod_uniface\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>Uniface</a></li><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: 10.4\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=uniface_10.4\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>10.4</a></li></ul></div></ul></header><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBody\" data-prismjs-copy=\"Copy\" data-prismjs-copy-error=\"Copy failed! Use Ctrl + C instead.\" data-prismjs-copy-success=\"Copied!\"><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBodyContent wide\" dir=\"ltr\"><div id=\"zDocsAiSummaryContaineruniface_104qdo1665702738098.html\"></div><div><article class=\"hascomments\" data-page=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/qdo1665702738098.html\" id=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/qdo1665702738098.html\"><main role=\"main\"><article aria-labelledby=\"ariaid-title1\" class=\"dita\" id=\"qdo1665702738098\" role=\"article\">\n<div class=\"body conbody\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__configuring_uniface_applications_to_use_tls_99484\"><p class=\"shortdesc\">Uniface supports the use of the TLS protocol to secure some or all communication\n      between Uniface servers, clients, databases, and external services such as email and web\n      services.</p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__p_d30527e1_d30528e1_d30529e1\">The Uniface TLS connector enables you to use certificate-based public-private key pairs to encrypt communication between communication peers.</p>\n<section class=\"section\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__topic_d20322e1_d20323e1_d20324e1_d20325e1_d20326e1\"><h2 class=\"title sectiontitle\" id=\"d1226963e52\">Example: Configure TLS with a Self-Signed Certificate </h2>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__p_d30533e1_d30534e1_d30535e1\">The following steps demonstrate how to configure a\n            desktop Uniface application to use TLS with a self-signed certificate for server\n            verification. (If you are interested in configuring TLS for a web application, see <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"xlb1665702738168.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/xlb1665702738168.html\" title=\"The TLS connector supports encrypted network connections between the Uniface Router and Uniface servlets—the Web Request Dispatcher (WRD) and SOAP Request Dispatcher (SRD). The servlet acts as a TLS client, which means the certificate of the Uniface Router must be verified before the connection can be established.\">TLS Connections for Uniface Servlets (WRD and SRD)</a> and <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"opu1665702738237.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/opu1665702738237.html\" title=\"Procedure to configure a TLS Connection for a Uniface Servlet (WRD or SRD).\">Configure a TLS Connection for a Uniface Servlet (WRD or SRD)</a>.</p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__p_d30536e1_d30537e1_d30538e1\">In this example, the Uniface Router is acting as the\n            TLS server, with the Uniface Server and Uniface client both acting as TLS clients.\n            Certificates and keys are expected to be in <span class=\"ph filepath\">\n<var class=\"keyword varname\">UnifaceInstallPath</var>/common/usys</span>. If you put them in a\n            different location, you need to reflect that in your configuration.</p>\n<ol class=\"ol\">\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15416e1_d15417e1_d15418e1\">\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__p_d30539e1_d30540e1_d30541e1\">Generate a self-signed certificate using\n                  OpenSSL</p>\n<div class=\"p\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__p_d30542e1_d30543e1_d30544e1\">\n<ul class=\"ul\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__ul_sky_c5c_2xb\">\n<li class=\"li\">You can use OpenSSL to generate keys and certificates, or your preferred\n                           tools.<div class=\"note note note_note\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__note_kwv_25c_2xb\"><span class=\"note__title\">Note:</span> On Windows, Uniface provides the\n      OpenSSL executable in the <span class=\"ph filepath\">/common/bin</span> folder of the Uniface installation.\n      On Linux, it is usually pre-installed. Alternatively, you can obtain it from one of the sites\n      suggested by the OpenSSL Wiki (<a class=\"xref\" href=\"https://wiki.openssl.org/index.php/Binaries\" rel=\"external noopener\" target=\"_blank\">https://wiki.openssl.org/index.php/Binaries</a>). For more information, consult the\n      OpenSSL documentation (<a class=\"xref\" href=\"http://www.openssl.org/\" rel=\"external noopener\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.openssl.org/</a>).</div></li>\n<li class=\"li\">The following command generates a self-signed certificate called\n                           <span class=\"ph filepath\">certificate.crt</span> and a private key called\n                           <span class=\"ph filepath\">privateKey.key</span> in <span class=\"ph filepath\">\n<var class=\"keyword varname\">UnifaceInstallPath</var>/common/usys</span>.<div class=\"code-toolbar\"><pre class=\"pre language-plaintext\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__pre_szd_g5c_2xb\" tabindex=\"0\"><code class=\"language-plaintext\">cd <var class=\"keyword varname\">UnifaceInstallPath</var>/common/usys \n../bin/openssl req -x509 -sha256 -nodes -days 365 -newkey rsa:2048 -keyout privateKey.key -out certificate.crt -subj /CN=*.<var class=\"keyword varname\">DomainName</var> -config=&lt;ConfigPath&gt;</code></pre><div class=\"toolbar\"><div class=\"toolbar-item\"><button class=\"copy-to-clipboard-button\" data-copy-state=\"copy\" type=\"button\"><span>Copy</span></button></div></div></div><p class=\"p\">where\n                              <var class=\"keyword varname\">UnifaceInstallPath</var> is the path to your Uniface\n                           installation, <var class=\"keyword varname\">DomainName</var> is the machine domain name,\n                           and <var class=\"keyword varname\">ConfigPath</var> is the path to the OpenSSL\n                           configuration file.</p><div class=\"note tip note_tip\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__note_c2l_35c_2xb\"><span class=\"note__title\">Tip:</span> To check\n                           the machine's domain name:<ul class=\"ul\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__ul_d2l_35c_2xb\">\n<li class=\"li\">Windows: Open the command prompt and enter the command\n                                    <kbd class=\"ph userinput\">wmic computersystem get domain</kbd>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\">Unix: Enter the command <kbd class=\"ph userinput\">hostname -d</kbd>\n</li>\n</ul></div><div class=\"note note note_note\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__note_z5c_xfr_2xb\"><span class=\"note__title\">Note:</span>\n<ul class=\"ul\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__ul_avc_xfr_2xb\">\n<li class=\"li\">There is an OpenSSL config file template inside the\n                                    <span class=\"ph filepath\">common\\bin</span> folder, that is\n                                    <span class=\"ph filepath\">common\\bin\\openssl.cnf</span>.</li>\n</ul>\n</div></li>\n<li class=\"li\">You can also configure the OpenSSL configuration file path by adding an\n                        environment variable as shown\n                        here:<div class=\"code-toolbar\"><pre class=\"pre codeblock language-plaintext\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__codeblock_bvc_xfr_2xb\" tabindex=\"0\"><code class=\"language-plaintext\">OPENSSL_CONF=<var class=\"keyword varname\">ConfigPath</var></code></pre><div class=\"toolbar\"><div class=\"toolbar-item\"><button class=\"copy-to-clipboard-button\" data-copy-state=\"copy\" type=\"button\"><span>Copy</span></button></div></div></div></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15425e1_d15426e1_d15427e1\">\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__p_d30557e1_d30558e1_d30559e1\">Edit the Uniface Router assignment file\n                     (<span class=\"ph filepath\">urouter.asn</span>)</p>\n<ol class=\"ol\" type=\"a\">\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15428e1_d15429e1_d15430e1\">Configure the TLS connector by defining a\n                     TLS profile and its associated settings, which specify the type of verification\n                     and the certificate and key to use. (The <span class=\"keyword cmdname\">usys</span> logical\n                     specifies that they are located in <span class=\"ph filepath\">/common/usys</span>).\n                     <div class=\"code-toolbar\"><pre class=\"pre language-plaintext\" tabindex=\"0\"><code class=\"language-plaintext\">[NET_SETTINGS]CertProfile verify_server=yes, server_certificate=usys:certificate.crt, server_key=usys:privateKey.key</code></pre><div class=\"toolbar\"><div class=\"toolbar-item\"><button class=\"copy-to-clipboard-button\" data-copy-state=\"copy\" type=\"button\"><span>Copy</span></button></div></div></div>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15431e1_d15432e1_d15433e1\">Change <span class=\"keyword cmdname\">$DEFAULT_NET</span> to\n                     use TLS: <div class=\"code-toolbar\"><pre class=\"pre language-plaintext\" tabindex=\"0\"><code class=\"language-plaintext\">[SETTINGS]$default_net = TLS:+14001:CertProfile|||</code></pre><div class=\"toolbar\"><div class=\"toolbar-item\"><button class=\"copy-to-clipboard-button\" data-copy-state=\"copy\" type=\"button\"><span>Copy</span></button></div></div></div>\n<ul class=\"ul\">\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15434e1_d15435e1_d15436e1\"><code class=\"ph codeph\">14001</code>—the port\n                           number (or any available port number). </li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15437e1_d15438e1_d15439e1\"><code class=\"ph codeph\">CertProfile</code>—name of\n                           a TLS profile. This can be any name but it must be the same in both the\n                              <span class=\"ph filepath\">urouter.asn</span> and the assignment files of clients\n                           and servers that connect to this Uniface Router. </li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15440e1_d15441e1_d15442e1\">Optional: Define a server to use instead of\n                     the <code class=\"ph codeph\">default</code> server. For example: <div class=\"code-toolbar\"><pre class=\"pre language-plaintext\" tabindex=\"0\"><code class=\"language-plaintext\">[SERVERS]SRV = <var class=\"keyword varname\">BinPath</var>/userver.exe /dir=<var class=\"keyword varname\">WorkingDir</var> /adm=<var class=\"keyword varname\">UnifaceInstallPath</var>/uniface/adm /asn=userver.asn</code></pre><div class=\"toolbar\"><div class=\"toolbar-item\"><button class=\"copy-to-clipboard-button\" data-copy-state=\"copy\" type=\"button\"><span>Copy</span></button></div></div></div>\n<ul class=\"ul\">\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15443e1_d15444e1_d15445e1\"><var class=\"keyword varname\">UnifaceBin</var>—path to\n                              <span class=\"ph filepath\">userver.exe</span> is present. Uniface installation's\n                           bin folder can also be used. </li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15446e1_d15447e1_d15448e1\"><var class=\"keyword varname\">WorkingDir</var>—your\n                           working directory path, or use an existing server UST definition as an\n                           example. </li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15449e1_d15450e1_d15451e1\"><var class=\"keyword varname\">UnifaceInstallPath</var>—Uniface installation path. </li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15452e1_d15453e1_d15454e1\">\n<div class=\"div dropDown\">\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__p_d30560e1_d30561e1_d30562e1\">Edit the Uniface Server assignment file\n                        (<span class=\"ph filepath\">userver.asn</span>)</p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__p_d30563e1_d30564e1_d30565e1\">Configure the TLS connector so the settings\n                     match the TLS server (Uniface Router) definitions:</p>\n<div class=\"code-toolbar\"><pre class=\"pre language-plaintext\" tabindex=\"0\"><code class=\"language-plaintext\">[NET_SETTINGS]CertProfile verify_server=yes, ca_certificate=usys:certificate.crt</code></pre><div class=\"toolbar\"><div class=\"toolbar-item\"><button class=\"copy-to-clipboard-button\" data-copy-state=\"copy\" type=\"button\"><span>Copy</span></button></div></div></div>\n</div>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15455e1_d15456e1_d15457e1\">\n<div class=\"div dropDown\">\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__p_d30566e1_d30567e1_d30568e1\">Edit the desktop client assignment file</p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__p_d30569e1_d30570e1_d30571e1\">Configure the TLS connector so the settings\n                     match the TLS server (Uniface Router) definitions:</p>\n<div class=\"code-toolbar\"><pre class=\"pre language-plaintext\" tabindex=\"0\"><code class=\"language-plaintext\">[NET_SETTINGS]CertProfile verify_server=yes, ca_certificate=usys:certificate.crt</code></pre><div class=\"toolbar\"><div class=\"toolbar-item\"><button class=\"copy-to-clipboard-button\" data-copy-state=\"copy\" type=\"button\"><span>Copy</span></button></div></div></div>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__p_d30572e1_d30573e1_d30574e1\">Change the desired path definitions to use\n                     the TLS connector with the desired profile. For example:</p>\n<div class=\"code-toolbar\"><pre class=\"pre language-plaintext\" tabindex=\"0\"><code class=\"language-plaintext\">[PATHS]$DEF TLS:+14001:CertProfile|<var class=\"keyword varname\">UserverUser</var>|<var class=\"keyword varname\">UserverPassword</var>\n                  </code></pre><div class=\"toolbar\"><div class=\"toolbar-item\"><button class=\"copy-to-clipboard-button\" data-copy-state=\"copy\" type=\"button\"><span>Copy</span></button></div></div></div>\n</div>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15458e1_d15459e1_d15460e1\">\n<div class=\"div dropDown\">\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__p_d30575e1_d30576e1_d30577e1\">Restart the Uniface Router, Uniface Server,\n                     and client application.</p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__p_d30578e1_d30579e1_d30580e1\">It should now work as before, but the\n                     communication channels are now encrypted.</p>\n</div>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<figure class=\"fig fignone\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__fig_wfn_1jv_hwb\"><figcaption><span class=\"fig--title-label\">Figure 1. </span>TLS Configuration for a Desktop Application</figcaption>\n<br/><img alt=\"TLS Configuration for a Desktop Application\" aria-label=\"Open image in gallery mode\" class=\"image expandable\" data-fancy=\"gallery\" data-gallery=\"gallery\" data-remote=\"https://docs-be.rocketsoftware.com/bundle/uniface_104/page/tlsconfiguration.png?_LANG=enus\" data-title=\"Figure 1. TLS Configuration for a Desktop Application\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__image_xfn_1jv_hwb\" role=\"button\" src=\"https://docs-be.rocketsoftware.com/bundle/uniface_104/page/tlsconfiguration.png?_LANG=enus\" style=\"cursor: pointer;\" tabindex=\"0\"/><br/>\n</figure>\n</section>\n<section class=\"section\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__topic_d20327e1_d20328e1_d20329e1_d20330e1_d20331e1\"><h2 class=\"title sectiontitle\" id=\"d1226963e343\">\n            \n More Information about TLS and Certificates\n </h2>\n<div class=\"table-wrap\"><table class=\"table\" count-columns=\"2\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__table_d3155e1_d3156e1_d3157e1\"><caption></caption><colgroup><col/><col/></colgroup><tbody class=\"tbody\">\n<tr class=\"row\" dir=\"ltr\">\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\">\n<p class=\"p\">\n                           About TLS \n                        </p>\n<ul class=\"ul\">\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15461e1_d15462e1_d15463e1\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"plc1665702545280.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/plc1665702545280.html\" title=\"Transport Layer Security (TLS) is a cryptographic protocol that provides secure communication over a computer network, including the Internet, WANs, and LANs. It is the successor of Secure Sockets Layer (SSL). Both are often referred to as SSL.\">TLS/SSL Protocol</a>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15464e1_d15465e1_d15466e1\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"kjy1665702545843.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/kjy1665702545843.html\" title=\"HTTP (HyperText Transfer Protocol) is the protocol that enables communication between a browser and a web site. The HTTPS protocol secures this communication by means of the TLS (Transport Layer Security) protocol and digital certificates.\">HTTPS Protocol</a>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15467e1_d15468e1_d15469e1\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"vua1665702738318.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/vua1665702738318.html\" title=\"Signed certificates are used to protect communication channels that conform to transport layer protocols such as TLS (Transport Layer Security) and HTTPS (Hypertext Transfer Protocol - Secure). They are used to authenticate peers in the conversation and to encrypt the data that is transferred.\">Transport Protocols and Certificates</a>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\">\n                        TLS Connector \n                        <ul class=\"ul\">\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15470e1_d15471e1_d15472e1\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"mow1665702545090.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/mow1665702545090.html\" title=\"The TLS network connector provides an encrypted network connection between the Uniface Router and its Uniface Servers and client applications. It can also be used by the UPOPMAIL component to connect to SMTP servers over TLS.\">TLS Connector</a>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15473e1_d15474e1_d15475e1\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"zdz1665702548111.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/zdz1665702548111.html\" title=\"When TLS is configured for certificate-based authentication, it uses signed certificates to guarantee the identity of communicating peers, and a negotiated master key for encrypting and decrypting the data. The certificate and its associated key make it possible to support a wide range of encryption ciphers.\">Certificate-Based Authentication</a>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15476e1_d15477e1_d15478e1\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"zwe1665702525639.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/zwe1665702525639.html\" title=\"A TLS connection profile is a named collection of TLS connector options that can be used to define multiple connections to Uniface Routers and Uniface Servers, each with its own configuration.\">TLS Connection Profiles</a>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"row\" dir=\"ltr\">\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\">\n<p class=\"p\">\n                           Configuring TLS \n                        </p>\n<ul class=\"ul\">\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15479e1_d15480e1_d15481e1\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"trs1665702548192.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/trs1665702548192.html\" title=\"To configure the TLS connector to use certificates to secure the connection and encrypt the data, you must enable server verification. If required, you can also enable client verification.\">Configure the TLS Connector to Use Certificates</a>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15482e1_d15483e1_d15484e1\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"bhc1665702738396.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/bhc1665702738396.html\" title=\"It is relatively easy to configure Uniface to use TLS using a pre-shared key, but it is not recommended for a production environment.\">Configure the TLS Connector with a Pre-Shared Key</a>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15485e1_d15486e1_d15487e1\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"fvi1665702723947.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/fvi1665702723947.html\" title=\"To enable server verification, you must set verify_server=yes in the assignment files of both TLS server and clients, and specify the certificates and public key used for encryption.\">Configure Server Verification for TLS</a>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15488e1_d15489e1_d15490e1\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"qoy1665702724029.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/qoy1665702724029.html\" title=\"To enable client verification, you must set verify_client=yes in the assignment files of both TLS server and clients, and specify the certificates and public key used for encryption in the TLS client assignment file. You must also specify verify_client_name to configure peer name verification in the TLS server assignment file.\">Configure Client Verification for TLS</a>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15491e1_d15492e1_d15493e1\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"opu1665702738237.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/opu1665702738237.html\" title=\"Procedure to configure a TLS Connection for a Uniface Servlet (WRD or SRD).\">Configure a TLS Connection for a Uniface Servlet (WRD or SRD)</a>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15494e1_d15495e1_d15496e1\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"uzk1665702679612.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/uzk1665702679612.html\" title=\"If you encounter connection problems using the TLS connector, these are usually the result of configuration errors, such as invalid or missing connector options, missing or incorrectly-specified certificates, or mismatched shared keys.\">TLS Troubleshooting</a>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\">\n<p class=\"p\">\n                           Configuration Settings \n                        </p>\n<ul class=\"ul\">\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15497e1_d15498e1_d15499e1\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"skw1665702542274.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/skw1665702542274.html\" title=\"You can assign connector options by setting USYS$TCP_PARAMS in the [DRIVER_SETTINGS] section of the assignment file.\">TCP Connector Options</a>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15500e1_d15501e1_d15502e1\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"rmh1665702524863.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/rmh1665702524863.html\" title=\"Set the default network path for clients, Uniface servers, or Uniface Routers.\">$DEFAULT_NET</a>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15503e1_d15504e1_d15505e1\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"hyi1665702739258.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/hyi1665702739258.html\" title=\"Use the [NET_SETTINGS] section of the assignment file to define TLS connection profiles, and their required keys or certificates. These can be used to configure different TLS connector paths.\">[NET_SETTINGS]</a>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15506e1_d15507e1_d15508e1\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"msq1665702542189.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/msq1665702542189.html\" title=\"Use the [DRIVER_SETTINGS] section of the assignment file to specify the database and component engine connectors used, and their parameter options. The options available depend on the connector in use.\">[DRIVER_SETTINGS]</a>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15509e1_d15510e1_d15511e1\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"gbz1665702543976.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/gbz1665702543976.html\" title=\"Use the [PATHS] section of the assignment file to define paths to network and database connectors, which connect to a Uniface Server, DBMS, or to another path. Path assignments can include path-to-connector assignments and path-to-path assignments.\">[PATHS]</a>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"row\" dir=\"ltr\">\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\">\n<p class=\"p\">\n                           About Digital Certificates \n                        </p>\n<ul class=\"ul\">\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15512e1_d15513e1_d15514e1\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"fer1665702676920.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/fer1665702676920.html\" title=\"A digital certificate (also known as a public key certificate) is a digitally-signed document used to validate the identity of the sender in communication between a client and server.\">Digital Certificates</a>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15515e1_d15516e1_d15517e1\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"cih1665702677297.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/cih1665702677297.html\" title=\"A Certificate Authority (CA) issues digital certificates that contain a public key and the identity of the owner. You can purchase signed certificates from a trusted third-party CA, or you can act as your own certificate authority.\">Certificate Authorities</a>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15518e1_d15519e1_d15520e1\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"gga1665702545367.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/gga1665702545367.html\" title=\"When the connection between a client and server is first established, either or both can verify the identify of the other by means of the other side's (or peer's) digital certificate.\">Certificate Verification</a>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15521e1_d15522e1_d15523e1\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"app1665702739332.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/app1665702739332.html\" title=\"The file format for certificates and keys may vary. Uniface uses the PEM (Privacy Enhanced Mail) format as specified by RFC 1421 for certificate files and key files. PEM encoding is a Base64 encoding with a header and footer and is also known as Base64 encoded DER.\">File Formats for Certificates and Keys</a>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n<td class=\"entry\" dir=\"ltr\">\n<p class=\"p\">\n                           Creating Certificates \n                        </p>\n<ul class=\"ul\">\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15524e1_d15525e1_d15526e1\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"pen1665702739479.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/pen1665702739479.html\" title=\"You can use tools such as OpenSSL to create certificates and generate RSA private and public keys for signature signing and verification. A self-signed TLS/SSL certificate is not signed by a publicly trusted certificate authority (CA) but instead by the developer or company that is responsible for the website; as a publicly trusted CA does not sign them, they are usually considered unsafe for public applications and websites.\">Creating Certificates</a>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15527e1_d15528e1_d15529e1\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"qso1665702548272.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/qso1665702548272.html\" title=\"A self-signed certificate is both the certificate and the trusted CA certificate with which it is validated. Self-signed certificates are commonly used when certificates are deployed internally within an organization.\">Create a Self-Signed Certificate</a>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"qdo1665702738098__li_d15530e1_d15531e1_d15532e1\">\n<a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"yta1665702677365.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/yta1665702677365.html\" title=\"You can act as your own certification authority when a digital certificate is deployed internally (as is often the case with Uniface applications).\">Acting as a Certificate Authority</a>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table></div>\n</section>\n</div>\n</article></main></article>\n</div></div></div><div class=\"bottomFeedback\"><div aria-labelledby=\"bottomFeedbackText\" class=\"bottomFeedbackContent\" role=\"group\"><span class=\"bottomFeedbackText\" id=\"bottomFeedbackText\">Was this topic helpful?</span><div class=\"bottomFeedbackButtonGroup\"><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_3615370\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-up\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-up\"></use></svg><span>Like</span></a><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_3615370\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-down\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-down\"></use></svg><span>Dislike</span></a></div></div></div><div style=\"position: fixed; bottom: 170px; right: 70px; cursor: pointer; transition-duration: 0.2s; transition-timing-function: linear; transition-delay: 0s; z-index: 3; opacity: 0; visibility: hidden; transition-property: opacity, visibility;\"><button aria-label=\"Scroll to top\" class=\"zDocsScrollTopBtn\" data-tooltip-content=\"Scroll to top\" data-tooltip-id=\"zDocsBackToTopToolTip\" id=\"zDocsScrollToTop\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-next\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-next\"></use></svg></button></div></body></html>", "text": "Configuring Uniface Applications to Use TLS Add to My Topics Add selected topic and subtopics Add Topic & Subtopics with topic head Add entire publication Watch Download PDF Save selected topic Save selected topic and subtopics Save entire publication Share Email Link Copy Link Feedback Last Updated Okt 05, 2024 Summarize Uniface 10.4 Uniface supports the use of the TLS protocol to secure some or all communication between Uniface servers, clients, databases, and external services such as email and web services. The Uniface TLS connector enables you to use certificate-based public-private key pairs to encrypt communication between communication peers. Example: Configure TLS with a Self-Signed Certificate The following steps demonstrate how to configure a desktop Uniface application to use TLS with a self-signed certificate for server verification. (If you are interested in configuring TLS for a web application, see TLS Connections for Uniface Servlets (WRD and SRD) and Configure a TLS Connection for a Uniface Servlet (WRD or SRD) . In this example, the Uniface Router is acting as the TLS server, with the Uniface Server and Uniface client both acting as TLS clients. Certificates and keys are expected to be in UnifaceInstallPath /common/usys . If you put them in a different location, you need to reflect that in your configuration. Generate a self-signed certificate using OpenSSL You can use OpenSSL to generate keys and certificates, or your preferred tools. Note: On Windows, Uniface provides the OpenSSL executable in the /common/bin folder of the Uniface installation. On Linux, it is usually pre-installed. Alternatively, you can obtain it from one of the sites suggested by the OpenSSL Wiki ( https://wiki.openssl.org/index.php/Binaries ). For more information, consult the OpenSSL documentation ( http://www.openssl.org/ ). The following command generates a self-signed certificate called certificate.crt and a private key called privateKey.key in UnifaceInstallPath /common/usys . cd UnifaceInstallPath /common/usys ../bin/openssl req -x509 -sha256 -nodes -days 365 -newkey rsa:2048 -keyout privateKey.key -out certificate.crt -subj /CN=*. DomainName -config=<ConfigPath> Copy where UnifaceInstallPath is the path to your Uniface installation, DomainName is the machine domain name, and ConfigPath is the path to the OpenSSL configuration file. Tip: To check the machine's domain name: Windows: Open the command prompt and enter the command wmic computersystem get domain Unix: Enter the command hostname -d Note: There is an OpenSSL config file template inside the common\\bin folder, that is common\\bin\\openssl.cnf . You can also configure the OpenSSL configuration file path by adding an environment variable as shown here: OPENSSL_CONF= ConfigPath Copy Edit the Uniface Router assignment file ( urouter.asn ) Configure the TLS connector by defining a TLS profile and its associated settings, which specify the type of verification and the certificate and key to use. (The usys logical specifies that they are located in /common/usys ). [NET_SETTINGS]CertProfile verify_server=yes, server_certificate=usys:certificate.crt, server_key=usys:privateKey.key Copy Change $DEFAULT_NET to use TLS: [SETTINGS]$default_net = TLS:+14001:CertProfile||| Copy 14001 —the port number (or any available port number). CertProfile —name of a TLS profile. This can be any name but it must be the same in both the urouter.asn and the assignment files of clients and servers that connect to this Uniface Router. Optional: Define a server to use instead of the default server. For example: [SERVERS]SRV = BinPath /userver.exe /dir= WorkingDir /adm= UnifaceInstallPath /uniface/adm /asn=userver.asn Copy UnifaceBin —path to userver.exe is present. Uniface installation's bin folder can also be used. WorkingDir —your working directory path, or use an existing server UST definition as an example. UnifaceInstallPath —Uniface installation path. Edit the Uniface Server assignment file ( userver.asn ) Configure the TLS connector so the settings match the TLS server (Uniface Router) definitions: [NET_SETTINGS]CertProfile verify_server=yes, ca_certificate=usys:certificate.crt Copy Edit the desktop client assignment file Configure the TLS connector so the settings match the TLS server (Uniface Router) definitions: [NET_SETTINGS]CertProfile verify_server=yes, ca_certificate=usys:certificate.crt Copy Change the desired path definitions to use the TLS connector with the desired profile. For example: [PATHS]$DEF TLS:+14001:CertProfile| UserverUser | UserverPassword Copy Restart the Uniface Router, Uniface Server, and client application. It should now work as before, but the communication channels are now encrypted. Figure 1. TLS Configuration for a Desktop Application More Information about TLS and Certificates About TLS TLS/SSL Protocol HTTPS Protocol Transport Protocols and Certificates TLS Connector TLS Connector Certificate-Based Authentication TLS Connection Profiles Configuring TLS Configure the TLS Connector to Use Certificates Configure the TLS Connector with a Pre-Shared Key Configure Server Verification for TLS Configure Client Verification for TLS Configure a TLS Connection for a Uniface Servlet (WRD or SRD) TLS Troubleshooting Configuration Settings TCP Connector Options $DEFAULT_NET [NET_SETTINGS] [DRIVER_SETTINGS] [PATHS] About Digital Certificates Digital Certificates Certificate Authorities Certificate Verification File Formats for Certificates and Keys Creating Certificates Creating Certificates Create a Self-Signed Certificate Acting as a Certificate Authority Was this topic helpful? Like Dislike"}